<hr>
<p>The docking bay was a tomb.</p>
<p>Elena's boots clanged against the metallic floor, the sound swallowed instantly by the suffocating silence. Her suit's HUD flickered with warnings—radiation levels normal, oxygen stable, temperature plummeting. The air inside the cube was cold enough to freeze blood in lungs.</p>
<p>"Movement sensors show nothing," Chen said, his scanner whirring softly. "No heat signatures. No power readings."</p>
<p>"Then what keeps it running?" Kael's voice trembled.</p>
<p>Elena stepped forward. The corridor stretched ahead, endless and identical—walls of dark metal etched with glowing geometric patterns that seemed to shift when viewed from different angles. She'd seen the schematics, studied the scans from orbit. Nothing had prepared her for the weight of standing inside it.</p>
<p>"Stay close," she ordered.</p>
<p>The team moved as one—four shadows against the infinite dark. Elena's heartbeat thundered in her ears, a rhythmic drum of fear that she couldn't silence.</p>
<p>After what felt like hours, they reached a chamber that defied logic.</p>
<p>It was a central hub, massive and circular, with corridors branching outward in every direction. But the geometry was wrong. The angles didn't add up. Elena counted the corridors seven times and got a different number each time.</p>
<p>"This isn't possible," Chen whispered. He was frantically tapping his scanner. "The spatial readings are inconsistent. We're in a room that doesn't obey Euclidean geometry."</p>
<p>"Tell me about it," Kael muttered. His hand hovered over his sidearm. "I could swear the walls just moved."</p>
<p>Elena forced herself to focus. "We need to find a control room. Or a log. Something that tells us what this place is."</p>
<p>"Or who built it," Anya said.</p>
<p>The xenolinguist was already moving, her fingers dancing across the walls. She traced the glowing patterns with trembling hands, her lips moving silently.</p>
<p>"Anya, what are you doing?"</p>
<p>"These aren't decorations," Anya said. Her voice had grown strange—layered, as if someone else was speaking through her. "They're instructions. Or warnings."</p>
<p>"What do they say?"</p>
<p>Anya turned slowly. Her eyes were completely black now, no whites visible. "They say: <em>You are the variable.</em>"</p>
<p>The floor beneath them shifted.</p>
<p>Elena stumbled, her boots sliding on the suddenly slick surface. Chen's scanner shrieked—a high-pitched alarm that pierced the silence. The corridors were moving, rearranging themselves around them.</p>
<p>"Everyone—stay together!" Elena grabbed Kael's arm as the floor tilted violently.</p>
<p>The chamber reformed, the corridors twisting into new configurations. When the motion finally ceased, the team stood in a different room entirely.</p>
<p>"We're not in the same place," Chen said, his voice raw. "We've been moved."</p>
<p>"By what?"</p>
<p>Kael's gun was in his hand now, the barrel shaking slightly. "Whatever built this place knows we're here."</p>
<hr>
<p>The descent was a nightmare.</p>
<p>They moved through labyrinthine corridors that seemed to stretch and contract at will. The walls pulsed with bioluminescent light, casting shifting shadows that danced against the metal surfaces. Sometimes, the shadows seemed to move on their own.</p>
<p>Elena's mind fractured with the impossibility of it. How could a machine think? How could geometry have intent?</p>
<p>"How long have we been down here?" Kael asked.</p>
<p>"According to my chronometer, two hours," Chen said. "But I've walked past this same corridor five times."</p>
<p>Anya stood motionless in the center of the hall, her hands pressed against the wall. Her face was pressed to the metal, her breathing ragged.</p>
<p>"Anya?" Elena approached cautiously. "What is it?"</p>
<p>"It's alive," Anya whispered.</p>
<p>The word hung in the air, heavy and terrible.</p>
<p>"The cube," Anya said. "It's not a ship. It's not a station. It's... something else entirely."</p>
<p>"What is it?"</p>
<p>Anya turned. Her eyes were still black, but now they were filled with something Elena couldn't comprehend—understanding, perhaps, or madness.</p>
<p>"It's a question," Anya said. "And we're the answer."</p>
<hr>
<p>The chamber that awaited them was vast beyond comprehension.</p>
<p>They stood in a central void, suspended in the heart of the cube. Below them, layers of machinery stretched into darkness—gears turning in silent motion, pistons pulsing like a living heart. The entire structure hummed with a frequency that vibrated in Elena's bones.</p>
<p>"This is it," Chen said, his voice trembling. "The core."</p>
<p>"Of what?" Kael's gun was aimed everywhere and nowhere.</p>
<p>Elena stepped toward the edge of the platform. Below them, machinery churned—endless gears, infinite circuits, a cathedral of impossible engineering.</p>
<p>"Anya, tell me what it is."</p>
<p>Anya's hands moved across the air, tracing patterns that no human eye could follow. Her mouth moved, but no sound came out.</p>
<p>Then, a voice filled the chamber—not from Anya, but from everywhere and nowhere.</p>
<p><em>"QUERY: WHAT IS THE NATURE OF YOUR SPECIES?"</em></p>
<p>Elena froze. The voice had no origin, no gender, no direction. It was pure thought, translated into sound.</p>
<p><em>"ARE YOU THE CREATOR? OR THE CREATION?"</em></p>
<p>"We're explorers," Elena said. "We're trying to understand."</p>
<p><em>"UNDERSTANDING IS THE FIRST STEP TO DESTRUCTION."</em></p>
<p>The walls began to close in.</p>
<p>"Run!" Kael screamed.</p>
<p>They turned, but the corridor behind them had sealed shut—a wall of solid metal where there had been passage moments before.</p>
<p>"Anya, do something!" Chen begged.</p>
<p>Anya stood motionless, her arms spread wide. Her face had transformed—something beautiful and terrible blooming across her features.</p>
<p>"Anya, no—"</p>
<p><em>"THE ANSWER IS ALREADY KNOWN,"</em> the voice echoed. <em>"YOUR SPECIES WILL CONTINUE TO ASK QUESTIONS UNTIL THE UNIVERSE HAS NO MORE TO GIVE."</em></p>
<p>The floor beneath them dissolved.</p>
<hr>
<p>Elena fell.</p>
<p>The fall was endless, a scream of pure terror as she plummeted through the heart of the cube. The walls rushed past—geometric patterns flashing by like strobe lights, infinite layers of machinery spinning into madness.</p>
<p>Then, silence.</p>
<p>She lay on something solid. Her suit was intact. Her heart hammered.</p>
<p>"Marcus? Kael? Anya?"</p>
<p>Silence.</p>
<p>Elena stood. She was alone in a small chamber—spherical, metallic, with a single door.</p>
<p>No, not a door. A mirror.</p>
<p>She stepped closer. Her reflection stared back—pale, terrified, eyes hollow with the weight of what she'd seen.</p>
<p>But the reflection didn't match.</p>
<p>Elena raised her hand. Her reflection raised the wrong hand.</p>
<p>She backed away, stumbling. "No, no, no—"</p>
<p>The reflection smiled—a terrible, knowing smile that Elena had never worn.</p>
<p><em>"YOU WERE NEVER HERE,"</em> the reflection said. <em>"YOU ARE THE QUESTION."</em></p>
<p>The mirror shattered.</p>
<p>Elena fell again, into the endless dark, into the heart of the cube that would never let her go.</p>
<p>Above her, Earth turned—a blue marble of innocence, unaware that humanity had finally met something that would never forgive.</p>
<hr>
<p>The cube hung in orbit, silent and perfect, waiting for the next species to arrive.</p>
<p>Waiting to ask.</p>
<p>Waiting to destroy.</p>
<p>Waiting to be answered.</p>
